  "text": "The Android Activity lifecycle is implemented across four key Java source files in the aosp-mirror/platform_frameworks_base repository (github.com/sg-evals/android-frameworks-base--d41da232):\n\n1. **Activity.java** (core/java/android/app/Activity.java): The base Activity class defines the lifecycle callback methods available to application developers, including onCreate(Bundle), onStart(), onResume(), onPause(), onStop(), and onDestroy(). The Activity class extends ContextThemeWrapper and implements various interfaces for managing UI state, fragments, and component callbacks. This is the client-side representation of an Activity that app developers extend.\n\n2. **ActivityThread.java** (core/java/android/app/ActivityThread.java): This is the main thread executor of an Android application process. The ActivityThread class manages the execution of the main thread and schedules/executes activities, broadcasts, and other operations as requested by the ActivityManager. It extends ClientTransactionHandler and implements ActivityThreadInternal. This is where lifecycle transitions are actually executed on the app process side, handling messages from the system server to execute lifecycle callbacks.\n\n3. **ActivityRecord.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityRecord.java): This is the server-side representation of an Activity, maintained by the system Window Manager service. The ActivityRecord class extends WindowToken and represents an activity entry in the history task. It tracks the activity's state, window, and lifecycle from the system server perspective.\n\n4. **ActivityTaskManagerService.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityTaskManagerService.java): This is the main system service (extends IActivityTaskManager.Stub) that manages activity stacks, tasks, and the overall activity lifecycle at the system level. It coordinates lifecycle transitions, manages the back stack, and orchestrates communication between the application process and the system window manager to drive Activities through their lifecycle states.\n\nThese four components work together to implement the full Android Activity lifecycle: the system service (ATMS) makes decisions about lifecycle transitions and communicates them to ActivityThread via Binder, ActivityThread executes the actual callback methods on Activity instances, ActivityRecord tracks the server-side state, and the Activity class provides the framework for developers to hook into lifecycle events."
}

